body:
@Eis-D-Z

> I personally guess that ideally at some point even the requests logic will become async for libcloud, until then yes, I agree that list_nodes() should have an async_list_nodes and the event loop better to be set at driver level, since the driver might not be on the main thread, or someone might want two drivers on separate threads etc...

Would you mind making that change? Aka adding ``async_list_nodes`` method instead of using ``async_`` kwargs.

@danhunsaker Thanks.

And, yeah looks like that one of the tests I added recently is causing PyPy to segfault for some reason.

For now I pushed a change so we skip that test under PyPy.

@sergerdn Thanks for the contribution.

Since it's a bigger change, can you please also sign an ICLA - https://libcloud.readthedocs.io/en/latest/development.html#contributing-bigger-changes?

EDIT: And sorry for the delay and congrats on your first PR!

@Eis-D-Z Since you recently modified pricing code, you might have some feedback / input on this change - d7ae996e509e71a9d148227c9d32613b09d6af59.

Imo, it's a right change and something we should have done a while ago when ``pricing.json`` file started growing...

In theory, if needed, we could also add new module level constant which can be changed by the user (e.g. ``libcloud.pricing.CACHE_ALL_PRICING_DATA = True``).

@Eis-D-Z Thanks for your feedback.

I pushed a change so this behavior can also be changed using module level variable - 3c73f668.

I think that's a good idea in addition to the function level argument, because most users don't call that function directly, but just utilize various drivers which call this function.
